abstract: The two progressive candidates seem to be trying to play down their differences that came into view over the past week. But many of their supporters were not ready to move on.
snippet: The two progressive candidates seem to be trying to play down their differences that came into view over the past week. But many of their supporters were not ready to move on.
lead_paragraph: EXETER, N.H. — Senator Bernie Sanders had just finished addressing supporters here Saturday afternoon, reprising his stump speech standards about raising the minimum wage, addressing climate change and implementing universal health care when a voter raised her hand to ask about a topic he didn’t mention but which had increasingly loomed over the race.

abstract: Senators Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren argue over what was said at a private 2018 meeting, their dispute takes center stage at the debate and Cory Booker says goodbye.

lead_paragraph: With less than three weeks to go before the Iowa caucuses, tensions escalated between two of the leading Democratic candidates and were on display on national television at a debate in Iowa.

abstract: Bill Weld tries a Granite State carom shot.
snippet: Bill Weld tries a Granite State carom shot.
lead_paragraph: Bill Weld, the former Massachusetts governor and current long-shot — make that, loooooooong-shot — candidate for the Republican Party’s presidential nomination, is a keen student of New Hampshire politics. In an interview with me this week, he noted the following fact: Every time an incumbent president of either party faced a significant primary challenge in the Granite State, he failed in his bid for re-election.

abstract: The multibillionaire presidential candidate who has flooded the country with television and digital ads has received a second extension from the Federal Election Commission.
snippet: The multibillionaire presidential candidate who has flooded the country with television and digital ads has received a second extension from the Federal Election Commission.
lead_paragraph: Michael R. Bloomberg, a multibillionaire who has flooded the country with more than $200 million in television and digital ads in his first two months as a presidential candidate, has requested and received an extension that will allow him to keep details of his vast personal fortune hidden until after millions of Americans vote in the 2020 primary.

headline_main: Michael Bloomberg Can Keep Details of His Wealth Hidden Until After Super Tuesday

abstract: Candidates like Andrew Yang and Michael R. Bloomberg, who were excluded from the last debate, can take a new path to the stage for the next one, to be held Feb. 7 in New Hampshire.
snippet: Candidates like Andrew Yang and Michael R. Bloomberg, who were excluded from the last debate, can take a new path to the stage for the next one, to be held Feb. 7 in New Hampshire.
lead_paragraph: There will be two ways for Democratic candidates to qualify for their party’s next presidential debate, scheduled for Feb. 7, the Democratic National Committee announced on Friday. All six candidates who qualified for this past week’s debate have qualified for the next.

headline_main: Democrats Can Qualify for the Next Debate by Winning a Single Delegate in Iowa

abstract: In the Trump era, some voters say the power of a symbolic first is overshadowed by anxiety about defeating him.
snippet: In the Trump era, some voters say the power of a symbolic first is overshadowed by anxiety about defeating him.
lead_paragraph: WINTERSET, Iowa — Almost exactly three years ago, Leila Schlenker marveled at the crowds at the Women’s March in Des Moines, which drew more than 26,000 people to the grounds of the state capitol and reminded her of the large social protests of the 1960s.

abstract: Thousands of readers told us who they think should lead the Democratic Party — and the country.
snippet: Thousands of readers told us who they think should lead the Democratic Party — and the country.
lead_paragraph: On Sunday, The New York Times’s editorial board will announce which Democratic candidate it’s endorsing in the 2020 presidential race. This year, the board experimented with a new level of openness — publishing transcripts of the interviews with each of the candidates that led to its decision.
